MORE INFO: Hand-Illustrated Rendering Style

The Heritage Atlas preset should not resemble a modern vector interface. Instead, every visual element should appear as though it has been carefully hand-drawn by an illustrator for a beautifully printed engineering atlas.

The goal is not to simulate low quality or poor craftsmanship. Instead, it should emulate the subtle imperfections naturally produced by traditional pen-and-ink illustration, engraving, and historical printing techniques.

The artwork should feel handcrafted rather than computer generated.

Organic Linework

Perfectly straight digital lines should be avoided whenever they are decorative.

Instead, linework should exhibit subtle organic variation, including:

Slight hand-drawn wobble
Tiny variations in line thickness
Minor asymmetry
Natural curve variation
Ink pooling at corners
Slight feathering
Gentle pressure variation

These imperfections should be extremely subtle—just enough to remove the sterile appearance of modern vector graphics while maintaining a polished, professional look.

Ink & Print Characteristics

Claude should design the artwork as though it were created using archival ink on fine drawing paper.

Illustrations may exhibit restrained characteristics such as:

Slight ink bleed into the paper
Tiny irregularities along edges
Mild texture within filled areas
Soft feathering where ink meets paper fibers
Occasional broken line segments from dry pen strokes
Delicate engraving hatch marks
Fine cross-hatching for shadows

The goal is to capture the warmth and authenticity of handcrafted technical illustrations, not to make the artwork appear damaged or distressed.

Historical Print Finish

The interface should feel like it was printed using traditional bookmaking techniques.

Visual elements should subtly evoke:

Lithographic prints
