Layout

The application should be organized into four dedicated workspaces.

Left Tool Palette

A narrow, vertically oriented toolbar positioned along the left edge of the screen.

The toolbar should contain only custom illustrated icons by default, with no visible text labels. Tool names should appear only when the user hovers over an icon, either as an elegant tooltip or by temporarily expanding the toolbar to reveal labels.

The toolbar should include tools such as Selection, Roads, Nodes, Buildings, Traffic Controls, Layers, Terrain, Analysis, Simulation, and Settings.

The panel should be fully resizable, collapsible, and integrated into the Heritage Atlas visual language with engraved borders and decorative framing.

Center Simulation Workspace

The center of the application should remain dedicated to the simulation viewport.

This area should occupy the majority of the available screen space and display the traffic simulation using the handcrafted illustration style described above.

All rendered elements—including roads, vehicles, buildings, overlays, selection indicators, and the editor grid—should inherit the Heritage Atlas aesthetic.

The viewport should remain visually clean, with decorative elements confined to its borders so they never interfere with editing or readability.

Right Analysis & Inspector Panel

The right side of the interface should contain an adjustable, scrollable Analysis & Inspector panel.

This panel should house all object properties, simulation statistics, network analytics, graphs, route information, performance metrics, layer management, and editor settings.

Information should be organized into beautifully framed cards resembling chapters in a historical engineering reference book.

The panel should support resizing, collapsing, scrolling, and expandable sections while maintaining the handcrafted decorative style.

Bottom Simulation Control Bar

A dedicated Simulation Control Bar should span the bottom of the application, serving as the central workspace for all playback and timeline controls.

This panel should be independent from the left and right sidebars and fully resizable in height. Users should be able to drag its top edge to expand it into a detailed control dashboard or collapse it into a compact status strip. The simulation viewport should automatically resize to accommodate these changes.

The control bar should contain all time-related controls, including:

