IMPORTANT REQUIREMENTS: 
Botanical Manuscript Style Specification
Artistic Direction

The entire interface must appear as though it was hand illustrated on aged paper using dip pen ink and watercolor, similar to the reference botanical illustration.

This is not a modern interface with botanical decorations. The interface itself is the illustration.

Every panel, button, icon, border, divider, label, control, and decorative element must feel as though it was physically drawn by an illustrator in a botanical journal or fairy field guide before being scanned into the computer.

The interface should evoke an antique illustrated manuscript rather than contemporary software.

Primary Artistic Medium

Every interface element should appear to have been created using only these traditional materials:

Dip pen or fine brush with waterproof ink
Watercolor washes
Handmade textured paper

Nothing should resemble modern digital vector artwork.

Ink Linework

Ink outlines are the foundation of the entire interface.

Every visible object—including windows, buttons, sliders, icons, borders, scrollbars, decorative flourishes, frames, tabs, illustrations, and text embellishments—must be enclosed by expressive hand-drawn ink outlines.

These outlines must exhibit:

Natural variation in line thickness
Visible pressure changes from the pen
Slight waviness rather than mathematically perfect curves
Organic imperfections
Tapered line endings
Small ink pools where strokes meet
Slight feathering and ink bleed into the paper
Tiny inconsistencies between repeated elements

No outline should ever appear perfectly uniform or mechanically generated.

Avoid perfectly straight lines whenever possible. Even long borders should contain subtle hand-drawn movement.

Ink should be a warm dark brown or charcoal black rather than pure digital black.

Watercolor Rendering

All color should be painted as watercolor rather than digitally filled.

Watercolor should include:

Pigment pooling
Darker edges
Soft blooms
Uneven transparency
Slight granulation
Visible paper texture beneath the paint
Soft layering of multiple washes

Avoid:

Flat fills
Airbrushed shading
Digital gradients
Cell shading
Perfectly even colors

Every painted surface should feel physically brushed onto textured paper.

Paper

The paper is part of the artwork.

Use warm ivory or lightly aged cream paper.

The paper should include:

Visible fibers
Fine grain
Slight discoloration
Gentle aging
Soft stains
Light texture variation

The background should never be perfectly flat or pure white.

