Final Style Goal

At first glance, the interface should be mistaken for a high-resolution scan of a real hand-painted botanical journal. Only after interacting with it should it become apparent that it is a functional user interface. Every visible component should feel as though it was individually drawn with ink on textured paper and colored with watercolor by the same artist who created the botanical reference illustration. The interface should prioritize the authenticity of traditional illustration over the visual perfection of modern digital design.Readability and Scale

The handcrafted artistic style must remain clearly visible at normal viewing distance. The interface is not intended to reveal its detail only when zoomed in; the ink work and watercolor rendering should be immediately apparent during normal use.

All artistic features—including ink line variation, watercolor texture, paper grain, pigment pooling, decorative flourishes, and hand-drawn imperfections—must be rendered at a scale that is easily recognizable on a standard monitor.

The interface should never appear to be a modern UI with microscopic textures overlaid. Instead, the handcrafted qualities should define the appearance of every component and remain visible without magnification.

Prominence of Artistic Details

The artistic rendering should be intentionally exaggerated enough that users can immediately recognize the traditional media.

Specifically:

Ink line weight variation should be obvious rather than subtle.
Watercolor brush strokes should be visible without zooming.
Pigment pooling and darker watercolor edges should be noticeable.
Paper texture should remain visible behind all interface elements.
Hand-drawn irregularities should be large enough to read as intentional craftsmanship rather than compression artifacts.
Decorative outlines should be thick enough to define the interface while remaining elegant.
Botanical embellishments should be large enough to contribute to the interface's identity rather than becoming tiny unreadable decorations.

If a user cannot immediately tell that the interface is hand illustrated from a normal viewing distance, the artistic rendering is too subtle.

Rendering Priority

Visual clarity takes priority over photorealistic subtlety.

When choosing between:

perfectly realistic watercolor textures that are difficult to perceive, or
slightly exaggerated textures that remain clearly visible,

always choose the more visible option.

The handcrafted characteristics should be intentionally emphasized so they survive normal monitor resolution, browser scaling, UI scaling, and image compression.

Minimum Visibility Rule

Every decorative element and artistic treatment must remain recognizable at 100% application zoom on a standard desktop monitor.

Do not create textures that are only one or two pixels wide.

Do not rely on microscopic paper grain or nearly invisible line variation.

Instead, scale every artistic effect so it remains clearly visible during normal interaction.

The interface should communicate "ink on watercolor paper" immediately, without requiring the viewer to zoom in or inspect individual pixels.

I would also add one sentence that specifically prevents Claude from making the UI "too clean":

The artwork should be intentionally bold enough to read at UI scale. Treat the interface as a hand-painted illustration that happens to function as software, rather than software with subtle artistic effects. The ink outlines, watercolor shading, and paper texture should be one of the first things the user notices when viewing the application.

That wording encourages Claude to make the artistic treatment a primary visual feature, not a faint texture hidden in the background.